HEADWORD: Lustrate
<hw>Lus"trate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Lustrated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Lustrating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>lustratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>lustrare</ets> to lustrate, fr.
<ets>lustrum</ets>. See <er>Lustrum</er>.]</ety> <def>To make clear or
pure by means of a propitiatory offering; to purify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We must purge, and cleanse, and <qex>lustrate</qex> the whole
city.</q> <rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

